Here's a simple C++ function that converts Markdown-formatted text to HTML-formatted text. Note that this implementation only handles a subset of Markdown features, such as headers, emphasis, and links. You can extend it to support other Markdown elements as needed.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Replace Markdown headers with HTML headers
    html = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^(#+) (.*)$"), "<h$1>$2</h$1>");

    // Replace Markdown emphasis with HTML emphasis
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("(?<!\*)\*(.*?)(?!\*)\*"), "<em>$1</em>");

    // Replace Markdown links with HTML links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\[(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)"), "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Markdown to HTML\n\nThis is *emphasized* text.\n\n[Link to Google](https://www.google.com)";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This function uses the `std::regex_replace` function to replace Markdown patterns with their corresponding HTML equivalents. The regular expressions used in this example are:

1. `^(#+) (.*)$`: Matches one or more hash symbols (#) at the beginning of a line, followed by any number of characters. This pattern is used to replace Markdown headers with HTML headers.
2. `(?<!\*)\*(.*?)(?!\*)\*`: Matches any substring enclosed in asterisks that is not preceded or followed by an asterisk. This pattern is used to replace Markdown emphasis with HTML emphasis.
3. `\[(.*?)\]\((.*?)\)`: Matches any substring enclosed in square brackets, followed by any number of characters, and then enclosed in parentheses. This pattern is used to replace Markdown links with HTML links.

Remember that this implementation is a simple example and may not cover all Markdown use cases. You can extend the function to handle additional Markdown elements as needed.

